arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase VI: Late Nabataean pre CE 106 minor collapses and repairs. Probable early collapse of the Baroque Room and damage occurs in both the Anteroom and Shrine Room. The tabun in Room A is used to store CE 1st c. Nabataean fine wares. East 'Cistern" used as a dump. Bath Complex built.

The most interesting feature of the Trench was the excavation and exploration of the large water passage system that is leads for 0.50 m directly to the south and then curves to the west for approximately 8.56 m. An investigation into the canalization system showed at least one major branch approximately 6.45 m west from the opening that was blocked by debris leading towards the south. This substructure of water passage systems is part of the underpinnings of the bath complex. The system is composed of well-dressed regularly sized ashlars that compose the wall. Presumably these sidewalls were lined with hydraulic stucco that has now deteriorated. The roof structure of the water passage system is intricately conceived and different from canalization in the Great Temple complex. Great Temple canalization is composed of monumental ashlars laid lengthwise and crowned by flat capstones. The canalization system is of small regularly dressed ashlars also laid lengthwise. However the roof is composed of three rows of flat slabs cantilevered to create a triangular or peaked space interspersed with a round arch.
In the south architectural boundary of the trench extends further to the west outside the boundaries of the Trench.
excavated to 0.81 m north south-by- 0.56 m east west.
Construction of the Well Room and the canalization system.
